The Real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story comparable to the Exodus of the Israelites led by Moses out of Egypt.
I grew up with that.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven out of their strongholds in the south by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government at the beginning of the 1930s.
Pursued and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers and impassable pastureland, with Mao guiding the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope against incredibly bleak prospects, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, badly battered, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
To what extent does China's founding myth align with reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the beginning of the Long March, I embarked on a search for its traces.
It remains a frightening journey through areas that have changed little to this day, inaccessible and unbelievably poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps 500 are still alive today. I tracked down 40 of them and had conversations with them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or made it to the end, but their stories were extremely enlightening.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, barely taller than his gun, when he entered the Red Army.
He had no choice: they had arrested his father and would not let him go until Huang agreed.
He thought of desertion, but stayed, out of fear of being caught and shot.
Many were leaving.
Six weeks after the start of the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the first major engagement of the army on its march.
However, at most 15,000 died in the battle, the rest disappeared.
Another battle, which took place on the Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. Allegedly, 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of nationalist troops, who were guarding the chains of the Luding Bridge with machine guns, and cleared the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star over China, that crossing the Dadu River was the most significant event on the Long March as such, and it is so celebrated today.
However, documents I have viewed suggest that the General, who led the Division across the Dadu, initially told party historians a completely different story. "The thing wasn't as complicated as people later made it out to be," he said. "If you examine historical facts, you should respect the truth.
"How one represents them is a different matter."
The legend lives on like this.
There was only a bit of banter above the dice.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial position in the communist government.
The march participants didn't know where they were headed.
There were constant discussions about the ultimate goal.
When they met in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the March.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could hardly feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the freezing cold.
The women were ordered to turn around and return home, because there wasn't enough food.
About a month after the unification of the three Red Armies, the party decided that the Long March had to continue.
However, she saved Chiang Kai-shek's kidnapping by the general, whom Chiang had appointed to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
However, not for the 21,000 men and women of the West Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's archrival, and were tasked with bringing aid from Russia over the western Chinese border.
But Mao issued them contradictory orders, so that they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped in barren land, where survival was difficult, they were eradicated by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
However, she is missing from official historical records.
A Muslim commander took Wang Quanyan, the leading female officer, as his mistress.
That was enough to make her a traitor in the eyes of the party and to deny all the years she had devoted to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, despaired and persevered.
The hunger brought the soldiers to take hostages in order to extort ransom.
The liquidations continued until practically no more officers were left to take command in the battles.
When the marchers had doubts, they overcame them with the help of communist propaganda.
They accepted their martyrdom with a bravery and self-sacrifice that is unmatched in the history of China and other nations.
